{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510384"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:28:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:28:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11533"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583490"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:16:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:16:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11533"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11533"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.07,0.57,0.32,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4162"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107362"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4162"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2022-01-30T16:28:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-01T14:55:17+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2022-03-04T16:54:45+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-26 19:36:36"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11533"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"748"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89848"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"89"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5464"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39986"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89848"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107362"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with acute onset of right-sided headache. The headache began 48 hours ago and is exacerbated by chewing food. Earlier this morning, she experienced transient bilateral vision loss while washing dishes. Her medical history includes polymyalgia rheumatica. She does not take any regular medications. She does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.3\u00b0C. She has since regained her vision with visual acuity of 6/6 in both eyes. Initial laboratory blood tests showed a raised erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR). Intravenous methylprednisolone was initiated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA few days later, her symptoms have improved and vital signs are stable. A repeat blood test shows the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin 100 g/L (115-155)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count 15.3 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4-11)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelet count 268 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-450)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAbsolute neutrophil count 13 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (1.80-7.50)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAbsolute lymphocyte count 1.83 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (1.10-3.50)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMonocyte 0.35 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (0.20-0.80)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEosinophil 0.06 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (0.02-0.50)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBasophil 0.03 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (\u22640.10)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EC-reactive protein 10 mg/L (\u003C5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EESR 22 mm/hr (1-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s laboratory results?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Allergic reaction to corticosteroids","Acute bacterial infection","Corticosteroid-induced neutrophilia","Acute inflammatory process","Stress-induced neutrophilia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of giant cell arteritis (GCA): new-onset unilateral headache, jaw claudication (pain while chewing), and transient vision loss. She also has a history of polymyalgia rheumatica, which is associated with GCA. The elevated ESR supports this diagnosis, and she was appropriately started on high-dose corticosteroids (methylprednisolone).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorticosteroid-induced neutrophilia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely explanation for her current laboratory findings. Corticosteroids cause neutrophilia through two main mechanisms: inhibition of neutrophil apoptosis (programmed cell death) and promotion of neutrophil demargination (movement from the vascular endothelium into circulation). This typically results in an elevated neutrophil count within hours of administration. The patient\u0027s laboratory results show a significant neutrophilia (13 \u00d7 10\u2079/L) with otherwise normal differential counts, which is consistent with this effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute bacterial infection\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with more pronounced clinical symptoms of infection, higher inflammatory markers (her CRP is only mildly elevated at 10 mg/L), and potentially other changes in the differential white cell count. Additionally, her symptoms have improved rather than worsened, making infection less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllergic reaction to corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E is rare and would typically present with clinical manifestations such as rash, pruritus, or bronchospasm. Allergic reactions are often associated with eosinophilia rather than neutrophilia, and her eosinophil count is normal at 0.06 \u00d7 10\u2079/L.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute inflammatory process\u003C/strong\u003E from her underlying GCA would cause neutrophilia, but her symptoms have improved with treatment, and her inflammatory markers (CRP and ESR) have decreased significantly from initial presentation. The pattern of isolated neutrophilia without corresponding elevation in other inflammatory markers is more consistent with a medication effect than ongoing inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStress-induced neutrophilia\u003C/strong\u003E can occur due to increased catecholamine release during physiological stress, causing demargination of neutrophils. However, this typically results in a more modest elevation in neutrophil count and would be unlikely to persist for days after the acute stressor has resolved. The magnitude of neutrophilia and the temporal relationship with corticosteroid administration make medication-induced neutrophilia more likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Corticosteroids commonly cause neutrophilia by inhibiting neutrophil apoptosis and promoting demargination.","Giant cell arteritis presents with headache, jaw claudication, and visual disturbances, requiring prompt corticosteroid treatment.","Laboratory findings after corticosteroid treatment typically show neutrophilia with normal or reduced lymphocytes, eosinophils, and monocytes."],"references":["Silvestre-Roig C, Hidalgo A, Soehnlein O. Neutrophil heterogeneity: implications for homeostasis and pathogenesis. Blood 2016; 127:2173. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27002116/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89848"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11533"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89848"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-29T07:59:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-29T08:02:17+09:30","number":8,"notes":"Corrected white cell count from 12.2 to 15.3 \u00d7 10\u2079/L to accurately reflect sum of differential counts (13+1.83+0.35+0.06+0.03=15.27).","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-06-29T08:01:31+09:30","plagiarismScore":2.6,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-4162-8.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T214645Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=498157c42b5962e58cadfa69250853e35cc1b50f7bc7f435cb3bb3e5839b727a"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4162"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107362"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16432"}},"generation":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisionGenerations","id":"22779"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"